The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Tanvir ready to lead Pak attack
                                                                                                                                                                                                     CRICKET BRIEFS
                      
	Tanvir ready to lead Pak attack  
	Karachi: Left-arm pacer Sohail Tanvir, who topped the Indian Premier League bowlers list with 22 wickets, is ready to take on the responsibility of being Pakistans leading bowler in the absence of Shoaib Akhtar and Mohammed Asif.  
	Tanvir returned with Kamran Akmal and Shoaib from India Wednesday and told reporters at the airport he was ready to return to national duty.         
	Asked if he was prepared for the main bowlers role after the Asif incident, Tanvir said: I am ready. When I can perform in the IPL I can do more for my national team. Obviously I will try to better my IPL form while playing for Pakistan in the tri-series.         
	Sree elated         
	Kochi: Sreesanth on Wednesday said the IPL has helped him realising his long cherished dream of bowling with Australian speedster Brett Lee. Sreesanth and Lee were Kings XI Punjab teammates, which reached the IPL semi-final.         
	I have learnt a lot in the IPL. Sharing the new ball with Brett Lee was a dream come true for me, he said. Sharing the dressing room with great players was a good experience. I am thankful to the god that I was able to do well in the tourney, Sreesanth said.         
	Scholarship         
	Calcutta: After a fine performance for the Mumbai Indians in the IPL, Dhaval Kulkarni became the first recipient of the Dilip Sardesai Scholarship on Wednesday, says A Staff Reporter.         
	The under-19 pacer will visit Australia for a six-week training programme at the Australian Cricket Academy (ACA). The MCA would borne the expenses of his trip.         
	Meanwhile, Indias Under19 World Cup winning captain Virat Kohli along with Pradeep Sangwan and Tanmay Srivastava have been awarded the Border-Gavaskar Scholarship for 2008 will accompany Dhaval at the same training at ACA.         
	India manager         
	Calcutta: Arindam Ganguly, the Tripura Cricket Association secretary, has been appointed manager of the Indian team for the triangular series in Bangladesh, says A Staff Reporter.         
	According to a Board of Control for Cricket in India release, both Venkatesh Prasad and Robin Singh will continue as the bowling and fielding coach respectively for the series in Bangladesh and the Asia Cup.                                                                                                                            
